without further damage, although the homeowner was so traumatised he slept the
rest of the night at a friend’s house.Muhammad Arif, spokesman for environmental group Himpunan
Pegiat Alam, is quoted as saying:“The two elephants that entered the kitchen are still in
the vicinity of the settlement, because their habitat has been destroyed by the
people and turned into palm oil plantations.” This is an increasing problem in Indonesia. The country
is a leading supplier globally of palm oil, which is used for cooking,
cosmetics, and biofuel. The palm oil industry comes at a huge cost to the
environment and animals like elephants whose natural habitat is being destroyed
as more plantations are developed. 
